adigest.com/awards/1989/|work=[[Soap Opera Digest]]|publisher=soapoperadigest.com|accessdate=June 17, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303080752/http://www.soapoperadigest.com/awards/1989/|archivedate=March 3, 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Natalia Livingston]] (Alpha Omega) \u2013 actress, ''[[General Hospital]]''{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n*[[Beth Ostrosky-Stern]] (Alpha Theta) \u2013 actress, model, wife of [[Howard Stern]]{{citation needed|date=March 2012}}\n*[[Amanda Schull]] (Delta Omicron) \u2013 actress, [[Center Stage (2000 film)|''Center Stage'']], ''[[One Tree Hill (TV series)|One Tree Hill]]''{{citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n*[[Savitree Suttichanond]] (Beta Upsilon) \u2013 singer on [[TrueVisions]]'s [[Academy Fantasia]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n*[[Molly Sims]] (Delta Gamma) \u2013 actress, model<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n*[[Candace Whittemore Lovely]] (Eta) \u2013 painter<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n\n'''News media'''\n\n* [[Kiran Chetry]] (Alpha Pi) \u2013 [[CNN]] anchor<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Katie Couric]] (Beta Sigma) \u2013 news anchor, ''[[CBS Evening News]]''<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Catherine Crier]] (Theta Zeta) \u2013 award-winning broadcast journalist, best-selling author, and former [[Texas District Courts|Texas State District Judge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tridelta.org/Document/Alumna/Distinguished_Deltas_NewsMedia |title=Distinguished Deltas |publisher=Tri Delta |accessdate=2014-08-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304005003/https://www.tridelta.org/Document/Alumna/Distinguished_Deltas_NewsMedia |archivedate=March 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n* [[Hoda Kotb]] (Beta Nu) \u2013 news anchor<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Vinita Nair]] (Upsilon) \u2013 news anchor<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Deborah Norville]] (Alpha Rho) \u2013 news anchor<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Kathy Orr (meteorologist)|Kathy Orr]] (Omicron) \u2013 meteorologist<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Janet Shamlian]] \u2013 [[NBC]] news correspondent<ref>{{cit web | url=https://journalism.missouri.edu/alum/janet-shamlian/ |title=Janet Shamlian |publisher=University of Missouri School of Journalism }}</ref>\n* [[Sally Stapleton]] (Delta Xi) \u2013 award-winning journalist{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}\n\n'''Literature'''\n\n* [[Joan Didion]] (Pi) \u2013 author<ref>Didion, Joan. \"The White Album\". New York Noonday Press, 1994, p. 207.</ref>\n* [[Doris Kearns Goodwin]] (Alpha Upsilon) \u2013 [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning author and historian<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Jill Marie Landis]] (Phi Kappa) \u2013 author <ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Anne Rivers Siddons]] (Phi Theta) \u2013 author<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n\n'''Politics and public service'''\n\n* [[Kelley Paul|Kelley Ashby Paul]] (Delta Psi) \u2013 political figure, wife of [[Rand Paul|Sen. Rand Paul]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://dlynx.rhodes.edu/jspui/handle/10267/13734|title=The Lynx Student Annual|last=Students of Southwestern at Memphis|first=|publisher=Student Government Association|year=1982|isbn=|location=Memphis, TN|pages=89}}</ref> \n* [[Pamela Bondi]] (University of Florida | Alpha Psi) - Attorney General, State of Florida (2011\u2013present)\n* [[Lisa Boscola]] (Gamma Beta) \u2013 [[Pennsylvania State Senate]]<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Debra Bowen]] ([[Michigan State University|Phi Gamma]]) \u2013 [[California Secretary of State]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n* [[Bobbe Bridge]] (Theta Alpha) \u2013 Former Associate Justice of the [[Washington Supreme Court]]<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Kathy Castor]] (Alpha Omega) \u2013 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] Congresswoman for {{ushr|Florida|11|}}<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Nellie Connally]] (Theta Zeta) \u2013 Former [[First Lady]] of [[Texas]]<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Elizabeth Dole]] (Alpha Omicron) \u2013 U.S. Senator from [[North Carolina]], Former [[Secretary of Transportation]]<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Caroline Fayard]] (Gamma Gamma) \u2013 [[Louisiana]] political figure\n* [[Terry Gabreski]] (Delta Omega) \u2013 Vice Commander, [[Air Force Materiel Command]], Wright-Patterson Air Force Base<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Rita B. Garman]] (Delta Pi) \u2013 Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Illinois]]<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Adele Khoury Graham]] (Alpha Psi) \u2013 Former First Lady of [[Florida]] (1978\u20131986)<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n* [[Michelle Lujan Grisham|Michelle Lujan-Grisham]] (Phi Delta) \u2013 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Governor of New Mexico]] \n* [[Dina Habib Powell]] - U.S. Deputy National Security Advisor for Strategy]<ref>Rae Nadler, [https://books.google.com/books?id=1eMDAAAAMBAJ&pg=53&hl=en#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Marketing America: Dina Habib Powell\"], ''The Alcade'' (January/February 2007), pp. 53-55.</ref>\n* [[Helen F. Holt|Helen Froelich Holt]] (Upsilon) \u2013 Former [[Secretary of State of West Virginia]]<ref name=\"DDD\" />\n\n'''Sports'''\n\n*[[Sophie Caldwell]] (Gamma Gamma) \u2013 Finished 6th in the [[2014 Winter Olympics]] in the Olympic Women's Cross Country Freestyle Sprint. This is the best finish by any American woman in this event.<ref>{{cite web|author=http://www.sltrib.com |url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/sports/57528468-77/randall-race-medal-skier.html.csp |title=Olympics: U.S. skier Caldwell surprises, Randall disappoints &#124; The Salt Lake Tribune |publisher=Sltrib.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-20}}</ref>\n*[[Meryl Davis]] (Iota) \u2013 [[Ice Dancing at the 2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Olympic Gold Medalist Ice Dancer]]<ref name=\"bio1314\">{{cite web | url=http://www.isuresults.com/bios/isufs00006260.htm | title = Meryl DAVIS / Charlie WHITE: 2013/2014 | publisher = International Skating Union | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140210012137/http://www.isuresults.com/bios/isufs00006260.htm | archivedate = February 10, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Marianna Davis|Muffy Davis]] (Omega) \u2013 Paralympic cyclist, [[sit-ski]]er and mountain climber<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title = Distinguished Deltas|url = http://www.tridelta.org/alumnae/distinguished-deltas/|accessdate = 2015-09-18|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150915213123/http://www.tridelta.org/alumnae/distinguished-deltas/|archivedate = September 15, 2015|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n* Roberta Cullen (Iota) \u2013 Shot Put, 1954 Olympics <ref name=\":0\"/>\n*[[Annika Dries]] (Omega) \u2013 [[Water polo at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2012 Olympic Gold Medalist Water Polo]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usawaterpolo.org/Home.aspx|title=USAWATERPOLO.ORG|accessdate=January 14, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305230142/http://www.usawaterpolo.org/Home.aspx|archivedate=March 5, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*[[Abigail Johnston|Abby Johnston]] (Alpha Omicron) \u2013 [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Olympic]] Silver Medalist [[Synchronized diving|Synchronized Diving]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usadiving.org/bios/abby-johnston/ |title=Abby Johnston |publisher=USA Diving |date=1989-11-16 |accessdate=2014-08-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120731184950/http://www.usadiving.org/bios/abby-johnston/ |archive-date=July 31, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Mariya Koroleva]] (Omega) \u2013 [[Synchronized swimming at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's duet|2012 USA Olympic Synchronized Swimming]] Duet Team<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usasynchro.org/Events/internationalevents/London_2012.htm |title=USA Synchronized Swimming |publisher=Usasynchro.org |accessdate=2014-08-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812185734/http://www.usasynchro.org/Events/internationalevents/London_2012.htm |archive-date=August 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notable controversies==\nIn 2009, the chapter at [[Miami University]] was suspended for hazing. Pledges were blindfolded and taken off-campus, where they were given an excessive amount of alcohol, causing some women to need medical attention after the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journal-news.com/news/news/local/sororities-drunken-actions-shock-miami-alumni-st-1/nNCtS/|title=Sororities\u2019 drunken actions shock MIami alumni, students|publisher=|accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the chapter at [[Pennsylvania State University]] was shut down due to hazing and endangering new pledges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onwardstate.com/2009/12/04/another-one-bites-the-dust/|title=Another One Bites the Dust|work=Onward State|accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref> The Tri Delta national organization refused to release specific details about the investigation.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20091207023705/https://www.collegian.psu.edu/archive/2009/12/04/delta_delta_delta_disbanded.aspx</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the chapter at the [[University of South Carolina]] was placed on probation after a party they hosted resulted in 31 citations for underage drinking. The sorority was forced to temporarily suspend all social activities as a result.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wistv.com/story/15420283/31-cited-for-underage-drinking-at-sc-party|title=Sorority puts chapter on probation after off-campus party bust|date=September 8, 2011|publisher=|accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 and 2014, sorority women from multiple chapters at the [[University of Alabama]] \u2013 including Delta Delta Delta, [[Pi Beta Phi]], [[Chi Omega]], [[Kappa Delta]], [[Alpha Gamma Delta]], [[Alpha Omicron Pi]], and [[Phi Mu]] \u2013 alleged that either active members or some of their alumnae had prevented them from offering membership to black candidates because of their race.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.marieclaire.com/culture/news/a10379/revolution-on-sorority-row-september-2014/|title=Revolution on Sorority Row|last=Webley Adler|first=Kayla|date=2014-08-06|work=Marie Claire|access-date=2018-06-27|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hercampus.com/life/greek-life/truth-about-racism-southern-sororities|title=The Truth About Racism at Southern Sororities|last=Gladu|first=Alex|date=2013-11-13|work=Her Campus|access-date=2018-06-27|language=en}}</ref> An anonymous Delta Delta Delta member spoke to the school newspaper, [[The Crimson White]], stating: \"To my knowledge, the president and the rush chair and our rush advisors [supported recruiting a black candidate], and if we had been able to pledge her, it would\u2019ve been an honor. However, our [alumnae] stepped in and went over us and had her dropped. The only thing that kept her back was the color of her skin in Tri Delt. She would have been a dog fight between all the sororities if she were white.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.al.com/tuscaloosa/2013/09/alabama_sorority_alumni_advise.html|title=Alabama sorority alumnae, advisers blocked black rushees, students say|last=Brown|first=Melissa|date=2013-09-11|work=AL.com|access-date=2018-08-26|language=en-US}}</ref> Students held a campus march to integrate Greek life on campus, and following media and national outcry, the university held a second round of recruitment in hopes of offering membership to more women, including black women.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nIn 2015, the chapter at the [[University of West Georgia]] was shut down for violating the university's policy and code of conduct.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewestgeorgian.com/tri-delta-chapter-charter-revoked-by-national-headquarters/|title=Tri-Delta chapter charter revoked by National Headquarters|work=The West Georgian|accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref> Serious allegations of hazing were charged against women of the sorority, and the Tri Delta executive board refused to release specific details of the investigation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fox5atlanta.com/news/33846856-story|title=Univ. of West Ga. Sorority Closed Following Hazing Allegations|author=FOX|work=WAGA|accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the chapter at [[Indiana University]] was shut down following an investigation which found that chapter members were \"involved in activities that do not represent our high standards or align with Tri Delta's purpose.\"<ref>https://www.heraldtimesonline.com/news/local/court-stay-blocks-eviction-of-iu-tri-delta-sorority-members/article_f14f38e8-1a09-11e7-9467-57e8108b06b7.html</ref> Chapter members also \"violated the chapter's previous probation terms.\"<ref>https://www.tridelta.org/news/tri-delta-delta-omicron-chapter-indiana-university/</ref> The national organization declined to specify further, but noted that the chapter had \"been on probation for three consecutive semesters, and each time was asked to take responsibility for their actions. Each time ... the chapter chose to ignore advice and recommendations, sending a strong message that they had no intention of making positive change.\"<ref>http://college.usatoday.com/2017/03/31/tri-delta-shut-indiana-university-evicted-house/</ref>\n\nOn January 20th, 2019, a member of Tri Delta sorority at the University of Oklahoma was removed from the organization after posting a video in which her friend appears wearing blackface and saying a racial slur. \n<ref>{{cite news |title=University of Oklahoma sorority kicks out member over racist blackface video |first= Mark |last= Osborne |newspaper= abc News |date= January 20, 2019 |url= https://abcnews.go.com/US/university-oklahoma-sorority-kicks-member-racist-blackface-video/story?id=60502553 |accessdate= January 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of social fraternities and sororities]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tridelta.org/ Tri Delta National Web Site]\n*[http://www.bodyimageprogram.org/ Reflections: Body Image Program Web site]\n{{National Panhellenic Conference|state=collapsed}}\n{{Fraternities and Sororities |collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Student organizations established in 1888]]\n[[Category:Student societies in the United States]]\n[[Category:National Panhellenic Conference]]\n[[Category:Women's organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:1888 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Boston University]]\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable controversies", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delta_Delta_Delta"}
{"title_page": "2017 IFA Shield", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox football tournament season\n| title                      = IFA Shield\n| year                       = 2017\n| other_titles               = IFA Shield 2017\n| image                      = \n| imagesize                  = \n| caption                    = \n| country                    = {{IND}}\n| dates                      = 14 May - 11 June 2017\n| num_teams                  = 25 (10 in final round)\n| champions                  = [[FC Pune City Youth]]\n| runner-up                  = [[Mohun Bagan A.C.|Mohun Bagan-SAIL Academy]]\n| matches                    = 39\n| goals                      = 90\n| attendance                 = \n| top goal scorer            = \n| player                     = \n| prevseason                 = [[2016 IFA Shield|2016]]\n| nextseason                 = [[2018 IFA Shield|2018]]\n}}\nThe '''2017 IFA Shield''' was the 121st edition of the [[IFA Shield]]. The tournament was designed as a U19 youth football tournament since 2015.That year, ten football clubs participated in final round. [[FC Pune City Youth|FC Pune City]] beat [[Mohun Bagan A.C.]] in final by 3\u20130 on 11 June 2017 to clinch their first [[IFA Shield]] title.\n\n==Venue==\nAll the matches were held at [[East Bengal Ground]], [[Mohun Bagan Ground]], [[Mohammedan Sporting Ground]] and Howrah Maidan.\n\n==Qualifying round==\n16 teams participated in the qualifying round and Pathachakra FC qualified to final round. Pathachakra defeated Kolkata XI by 1-1, (Pen 4-2) to enter the final round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kolkatafootball.com/ifa_shield_u19_2017/qlf_round_result.html|title=kolkatafootball.com{{!}}u19 IFA shield- 2017{{!}}Indian football live score|last=www.KolkataFootball.Com|website=kolkatafootball.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-12}}</ref>\n\n==Final round==\nFC Pune City beats Mohun Bagan A.C. in final by 3\u20130 on 11 June 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kolkatafootball.com/ifa_shield_u19_2017/final_round_result.html|title=kolkatafootball.com{{!}}u19 IFA shield- 2017{{!}}Indian football live score|last=www.KolkataFootball.Com|website=kolkatafootball.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{IFA seasons}}\n{{2016\u201317 in Indian football}}\n{{2017 in Asian football (AFC)}}\n\n[[Category:IFA Shield seasons]]\n[[Category:2016\u201317 in Indian football|Ifa Shield]]\n[[Category:2017 domestic association football cups|Ifa Shield]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox football tournament season\n| title                      = IFA Shield\n| year                       = 2017\n| other_titles               = IFA Shield 2017\n| image                      = \n| imagesize                  = \n| caption                    = \n| country                    = {{IND}}\n| dates                      = 14 May - 11 June 2017\n| num_teams                  = 25 (10 in final round)\n| champions                  = [[FC Pune City Youth]]\n| runner-up                  = [[Mohun Bagan A.C.|Mohun Bagan-SAIL Academy]]\n| matches                    = 39\n| goals                      = 90\n| attendance                 = \n| top goal scorer            = \n| player                     = \n| prevseason                 = [[2016 IFA Shield|2016]]\n| nextseason                 = [[2018 IFA Shield|2018]]\n}}\nThe 2017 IFA Shield was the 121st edition of the [[IFA Shield]]. The tournament was designed as a U19 youth football tournament since 2015.That year, ten football clubs participated in final round. [[FC Pune City Youth|FC Pune City]] beat [[Mohun Bagan A.C.]] in final by 3-0 on 11 June 2017 to clinch their first [[IFA Shield]] title.\n\n==Venue==\nAll the matches were held at [[East Bengal Ground]], [[Mohun Bagan Ground]], [[Mohammedan Sporting Ground]] and Howrah Maidan.\n\n==Qualifying round==\n16 teams participated in the qualifying round and Pathachakra FC qualified to final round. Pathachakra defeated Kolkata XI by 1-1, (Pen 4-2) to enter the final round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kolkatafootball.com/ifa_shield_u19_2017/qlf_round_result.html|title=kolkatafootball.com{{!}}u19 IFA shield- 2017{{!}}Indian football live score|last=www.KolkataFootball.Com|website=kolkatafootball.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-12}}</ref>\n\n==Final round==\nFC Pune City beats Mohun Bagan A.C. in final by 3-0 on 11 June 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kolkatafootball.com/ifa_shield_u19_2017/final_round_result.html|title=kolkatafootball.com{{!}}u19 IFA shield- 2017{{!}}Indian football live score|last=www.KolkataFootball.Com|website=kolkatafootball.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{IFA seasons}}\n{{2016\u201317 in Indian football}}\n{{2017 in Asian football (AFC)}}\n\n[[Category:IFA Shield seasons]]\n[[Category:2016\u201317 in Indian football|Ifa Shield]]\n[[Category:2017 domestic association football cups|Ifa Shield]]\n", "name_user": "Dewritech", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 3-0 \u2192 3\u20130 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_IFA_Shield"}
{"title_page": "R. Tom Zuidema", "text_new": "'''Reiner Tom Zuidema''' (May 24, 1927 \u2013 March 2, 2016) was professor of [[Anthropology]] and Latin American and Caribbean Studies at [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]].<ref name=renner>{{cite web|title=Reiner \"Tom\" Zuidema|url=http://www.renner-wikoffchapel.com/fh/obituaries/obituary.cfm?o_id=3623278&fh_id=10562|publisher=Renner-Wikoff Chapel|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>http://www.anthro.illinois.edu/people/rtzuidem. Retrieved July 5, 2011.</ref> He is well known for his seminal contributions on [[Inca civilization|Inca]] social and political organization. His early work consisted of a structural analysis of the ceque system. He later extended this approach, based on French and Dutch [[structuralism]], to other aspects of Andean civilization, notably [[kinship]], the Inca calendar and Incaic understanding of [[astronomy]].<ref>Morris, Craig. 2007. Andean Ethnohistory and the Agenda for Inka Archaeology. In ''Variations in the expression of Inka power: a symposium at Dumbarton Oaks, 18 and 19 October 1997'', ed. [[Richard L. Burger]], Craig Morris, and Ramiro Matos Mendieta, 1-10. Washington, D.C.: Dumbarton Oaks.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nZuidema was born in [[Haarlem]], the Netherlands. He obtained a PhD in his home country and later moved to the United States.<ref name=renner/> He had started studying Indonesian social sciences but later switched to anthropology of South America.<ref name=renner/> The main reason for this was that Indonesia became independent of the Netherlands, and he could not work in the country anymore.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jacqueline Fowks |url=http://internacional.elpais.com/internacional/2016/03/05/actualidad/1457140702_640465.html |title=Tom Zuidema, \u2018el Indiana Jones\u2019 del Imperio inca |language=Spanish |newspaper=El Pa\u00eds |date=5 March 2016 |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> Zuidema studied Spanish in [[Madrid]] and moved to Peru in 1957. He published a study on the {{Interlanguage link multi|Ceque|es}} (lines) of [[Cusco]] in 1962.<ref name=comercio>{{cite news|author=Lilia C\u00f3rdova T\u00e1bori |url=http://elcomercio.pe/huellas-digitales/archivo/fallece-tom-zuidema-destacado-antropologo-holandes-noticia-1883994 |title=Fallece Tom Zuidema, destacado antrop\u00f3logo holand\u00e9s |language=Spanish |newspaper=[[El Comercio (Peru)|El Comercio]] |date=4 March 2016 |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> In 1964 Zuidema moved his family to Peru and started teaching at [[San Crist\u00f3bal of Huamanga University]]. After three years he returned to the United States and started working at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. In 1993 he retired.<ref name=renner/>\n\nIn 1977 Zuidema became a correspondent of the [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.knaw.nl/en/members/correspondents/5063 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304053211/https://www.knaw.nl/en/members/correspondents/5063 |title=R.T. Zuidema |publisher=Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences |date= |archive-date=4 March 2016 |accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref> He was awarded an honorary doctorate by the [[Pontifical Catholic University of Peru]] in 1993.<ref name=comercio/>\n\n== Publications (selection) ==\n*1964. ''The ceque system of Cuzco: the social organization of the capital of the Inca''. Trans. Eva M. Hooykaas. Archives Internationales d\u2019Ethnographie 50. Leiden: Brill.\n*1977. The Inca Calendar. In ''Native American Astronomy'', 1:221-259. Austin: University of Texas Press.\n*1981. Inca Observations of the Solar and Lunar Passages Through Zenith and Anti- Zenith at Cuzco. In ''Archaeoastronomy in the Americas'', ed. Ray A. Williamson, 319\u2013342. Los Altos: Ballena Press.\n*1983. \u201cHierarchy and Space in Incaic Social Organization.\u201d ''Ethnohistory'' 30 (2): 49\u201375.\n*1990. ''Inca Civilization in Cuzco''. Trans. Jean-Jacques Decoster. Austin: University of Texas Press.\n*2011a. El Calendario Inca. Tiempo y Espacio en la Organizacion Ritual del Cuzco. La idea del pasado. Lima: Fondo Editorial del Congreso del Peru. pp.&nbsp;906\n*2011b. \"Chuquibamba Textiles and their Interacting Systems of Notation. In: Their Way of Writing. Scripts, Signs, and Pictographs in Pre-Columbian America. E. Boone and G. Urton, eds. Washington D.C.: Dumbarton Oaks, pp. 251-275.\n*2014a \"Hacer calendarios\" en Quipus y Tejidos. Los Numeros y su Rol en el Registro Simultaneo del Orden Sociopolitico y Calendarico Andino en El Cuzco, Chuquibamba y Collaguas. In: Sistemas de notacion Inca: Quipu y Tocapu. Actas del Simposio Internacional, Lima 15-17 de Enero de 2009. Carmen Arellano Hoffman, Editora. Peru, Ministerio de Cultura, Museo Nacional de Arqueologia, Antropologia e Historia del Peru. Proyecto QhapagNan, pp.&nbsp;397\u2013444\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.anthro.illinois.edu/people/rtzuidem\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zuidema, R. Tom}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:American anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:People from Haarlem]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign faculty]]\n", "text_old": "'''Reiner Tom Zuidema''' (May 24, 1927 \u2013 March 2, 2016) was professor of [[Anthropology]] and Latin American and Caribbean Studies at [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]].<ref name=renner>{{cite web|title=Reiner \"Tom\" Zuidema|url=http://www.renner-wikoffchapel.com/fh/obituaries/obituary.cfm?o_id=3623278&fh_id=10562|publisher=Renner-Wikoff Chapel|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref>http://www.anthro.illinois.edu/people/rtzuidem. Retrieved July 5, 2011.</ref> He is well known for his seminal contributions on [[Inca civilization|Inca]] social and political organization. His early work consisted of a structural analysis of the ceque system. He later extended this approach, based on French and Dutch [[structuralism]], to other aspects of Andean civilization, notably [[kinship]], the Inca calendar and Incaic understanding of [[astronomy]].<ref>Morris, Craig. 2007. Andean Ethnohistory and the Agenda for Inka Archaeology. In ''Variations in the expression of Inka power: a symposium at Dumbarton Oaks, 18 and 19 October 1997'', ed. [[Richard L. Burger]], Craig Morris, and Ramiro Matos Mendieta, 1-10. Washington, D.C.: Dumbarton Oaks.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nZuidema was born in [[Haarlem]], the Netherlands. He obtained a PhD in his home country and later moved to the United States.<ref name=renner/> He had started studying Indonesian social sciences but later switched to anthropology of South America.<ref name=renner/> The main reason for this was that Indonesia became independent of the Netherlands, and he could not work in the country anymore.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jacqueline Fowks |url=http://internacional.elpais.com/internacional/2016/03/05/actualidad/1457140702_640465.html |title=Tom Zuidema, \u2018el Indiana Jones\u2019 del Imperio inca |language=Spanish |newspaper=El Pa\u00eds |date=5 March 2016 |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> Zuidema studied Spanish in [[Madrid]] and moved to Peru in 1957. He published a study on the {{Interlanguage link multi|Ceque|es}} (lines) of [[Cusco]] in 1962.<ref name=comercio>{{cite news|author=Lilia C\u00f3rdova T\u00e1bori |url=http://elcomercio.pe/huellas-digitales/archivo/fallece-tom-zuidema-destacado-antropologo-holandes-noticia-1883994 |title=Fallece Tom Zuidema, destacado antrop\u00f3logo holand\u00e9s |language=Spanish |newspaper=[[El Comercio (Peru)|El Comercio]] |date=4 March 2016 |accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> In 1964 Zuidema moved his family to Peru and started teaching at [[San Crist\u00f3bal of Huamanga University]]. After three years he returned to the United States and started working at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. In 1993 he retired.<ref name=renner/>\n\nIn 1977 Zuidema became a correspondent of the [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.knaw.nl/en/members/correspondents/5063 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304053211/https://www.knaw.nl/en/members/correspondents/5063 |title=R.T. Zuidema |publisher=Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences |date= |archive-date=4 March 2016 |accessdate=28 March 2016}}</ref> He was awarded an honorary doctorate by the [[Pontifical Catholic University of Peru]] in 1993.<ref name=comercio/>\n\n== Publications (selection) ==\n*1964. ''The ceque system of Cuzco: the social organization of the capital of the Inca''. Trans. Eva M. Hooykaas. Archives Internationales d\u2019Ethnographie 50. Leiden: Brill.\n*1977. The Inca Calendar. In ''Native American Astronomy'', 1:221-259. Austin: University of Texas Press.\n*1981. Inca Observations of the Solar and Lunar Passages Through Zenith and Anti- Zenith at Cuzco. In ''Archaeoastronomy in the Americas'', ed. Ray A. Williamson, 319-342. Los Altos: Ballena Press.\n*1983. \u201cHierarchy and Space in Incaic Social Organization.\u201d ''Ethnohistory'' 30 (2): 49-75.\n*1990. ''Inca Civilization in Cuzco''. Trans. Jean-Jacques Decoster. Austin: University of Texas Press.\n*2011a. El Calendario Inca. Tiempo y Espacio en la Organizacion Ritual del Cuzco. La idea del pasado. Lima: Fondo Editorial del Congreso del Peru. pp. 906\n*2011b. \"Chuquibamba Textiles and their Interacting Systems of Notation. In: Their Way of Writing. Scripts, Signs, and Pictographs in Pre-Columbian America. E. Boone and G. Urton, eds. Washington D.C.: Dumbarton Oaks, pp. 251-275.\n*2014a \"Hacer calendarios\" en Quipus y Tejidos. Los Numeros y su Rol en el Registro Simultaneo del Orden Sociopolitico y Calendarico Andino en El Cuzco, Chuquibamba y Collaguas. In: Sistemas de notacion Inca: Quipu y Tocapu. Actas del Simposio Internacional, Lima 15-17 de Enero de 2009. Carmen Arellano Hoffman, Editora. Peru, Ministerio de Cultura, Museo Nacional de Arqueologia, Antropologia e Historia del Peru. Proyecto QhapagNan, pp. 397-444\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.anthro.illinois.edu/people/rtzuidem\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zuidema, R. Tom}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:American anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:People from Haarlem]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Dewritech", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublications (selection):clean up,typo(s) fixed: 319-342 \u2192 319\u2013342 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R._Tom_Zuidema"}
{"title_page": "Calum Scott", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Calum Scott\n| image            = Ven16 ja 20jul calum.jpg\n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1988|10|12|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Kingston upon Hull]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| genre            = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar}}\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|The Experiment|Maroon 5|[[Ti\u00ebsto]]|[[Leona Lewis]]}}\n| Signature        = Scott Calum signature.svg\n}}\n''' Calum Scott '''(born 12 October 1988)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/experimentUK/status/521352815982022656/photo/1 |publisher=The Experiment |title=Happy birthday to our frontman Calum have a great day mate |date=12 October 2014}}</ref> is an English singer and songwriter. In 2013, he won a talent competition put on by his local newspaper.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Winter |first1=Phil |title=Calum Scott releases debut album with intimate Hull gig in HMV |url=https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife/calum-scott-releases-debut-album-1324384 |website=HullLive |publisher=Hull Daily Mail |accessdate=14 September 2018 |date=10 March 2018}}</ref> In 2015, he became known worldwide after competing on the popular television show ''[[Britain's Got Talent (series 9)|Britain's Got Talent]]''. He subsequently released his version of [[Robyn]]'s hit \"[[Dancing On My Own#Calum Scott version|Dancing On My Own]]\" as a single, which reached number two on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and became the best-selling song that summer in the UK. In 2018, he collaborated with [[Leona Lewis]] on the single \"[[You Are the Reason (Calum Scott song)|You Are the Reason]]\".\n\n==Career==\n===2013\u20132015: Career beginning and ''Britain's Got Talent''===\nOn 15 August 2013, Scott won the talent competition Mail's Star Search, organized by ''[[Hull Daily Mail]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Calum-Scott-talent-Winner-Star-Search-2013/story-19659977-detail/story.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706085842/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Calum-Scott-talent-Winner-Star-Search-2013/story-19659977-detail/story.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 July 2015 |title=Calum Scott talent: Winner of Star Search 2013 declared |work=[[Hull Daily Mail]] |date=15 August 2013 |accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> He then joined a [[Maroon 5]] [[tribute band]], Maroon 4, and toured around the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/star-search-2014-hull-new-theatre-stage-set/story-20800138-detail/story.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924045045/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/star-search-2014-hull-new-theatre-stage-set/story-20800138-detail/story.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 September 2015 |title=Star Search 2014: Hull New Theatre stage is set for talent to shine |work=[[Hull Daily Mail]]|accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> In 2014 he formed the [[electronic music|electronic]] duo, The Experiment with John McIntyre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flavourmag.co.uk/introducing-calum-scott/ |title=Introducing Calum Scott! |publisher=Flavourmag.co.uk |date=13 April 2015}}</ref> The debut single, \"Girl (You're Beautiful)\", was released on 14 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/girl-youre-beautiful-single/id1024796932|title=Girl (You're Beautiful)|work=iTunes|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref> The duo performed the song on ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]'' and ''[[BBC Look North (East Yorkshire and Lincolnshire)|BBC Look North]]'', but  after, broke up.<ref>{{cite web|title = My sister Jade's 'the inspiration behind my singing'|url = http://www.itv.com/goodmorningbritain/entertainment/callum-scott-britains-got-talent|website=Itv.com|accessdate = 6 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Timeline Photos \u2013 BBC Look North (East Yorkshire & Lincolnshire) {{!}} Facebook|url = https://www.facebook.com/BBCLookNorth/photos/a.126845094069777.34234.118450564909230/831343696953243/|website = Facebook.com|accessdate = 6 July 2015}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|title =  All Calum Scott Lyrics|url = https://www.lyricsgetit.com/calum-scott-lyrics-u59mkl.html|website = LyricsGetit.com|accessdate = 6 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 April 2015, Scott's audition for the [[Britain's Got Talent (series 9)|ninth series]] of ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'' was broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]. Just before his audition, his sister Jade also auditioned, but was stopped early on both of her songs by Simon Cowell. Jade received three \"No\" votes from [[Amanda Holden]], [[David Walliams]], and [[Simon Cowell]] ([[Alesha Dixon]]'s vote was unannounced as it was not needed). Despite obvious nerves at seeing his sister get rejected, Calum performed a cover of [[Robyn]]'s \"[[Dancing On My Own]]\", which he had heard [[Kings of Leon]] performing on [[BBC Radio 1]]'s ''[[Live Lounge]]'' in 2013. Following a standing ovation from the judging panel, Cowell pressed the Golden Buzzer giving Scott an automatic place in the live shows. Explaining his decision to send Scott straight to the semi-finals, Cowell said:\n{{quote2|\"I've never ever in all the years I've done this show heard a guy with the talent you've got. Seriously. And the version was sensational, and that shows to me that you're more than a singer, you're an artist and that's why you got that (the buzzer).\"}} After this audition, Scott received support from stars such as [[Little Mix]] and [[Ashton Kutcher]].<ref>{{cite web|title = BGT favourite Calum Scott on getting sex messages from fans|url = https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/bgt-favourite-calum-scott-sex-5742639|website=Mirror.co.uk|accessdate = 6 July 2015|first = Katy|last = Forrester}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his appearance on the show's first episode, his [[Twitter]] followers jumped from 400 to over 25,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/film/2015041324581/calum-scott-britains-got-talent-marriage-proposals/ |publisher=Hello Daily News |title=Simon Cowell's golden buzzer act Calum Scott already receiving marriage proposals |date=13 April 2015}}</ref> The video of his audition has been viewed over 276,000,000 times on [[YouTube]]. In the semi-final on 29 May, Scott performed \"[[We Don't Have to Take Our Clothes Off]]\" by [[Jermaine Stewart]]. Walliams commented \"You really sound like a recording artist\", whilst [[Alesha Dixon]] suggested that he could have \"success around the world\". He won the semi final with 25.6% of the vote, sending him straight through to the final. In the final on 31 May, Scott performed \"[[Diamonds (Rihanna song)|Diamonds]]\" by [[Rihanna]] and finished sixth out of 12 contestants with 8.2% of the vote. After ''Britain's Got Talent'', Scott embarked on a series of shows around the United Kingdom, including [[Viking FM]] Future Star Awards, [[Flamingo Land Resort|Flamingo Land Resort Fair]], [[Westwood Cross|Westwood Cross Shopping Centre]]'s tenth anniversary, Gibraltar Summer Nights, [[Hull Daily Mail]]'s Star and [[Dartford]] Festival.<ref>{{cite web|title = Future Star Receives Fundraising Award|url = http://thescunthorpeindependent.com/2015/06/30/future-star-receives-fundraising-award/|website = Scunthorpe Independent News|accessdate = 6 July 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150701080334/http://thescunthorpeindependent.com/2015/06/30/future-star-receives-fundraising-award/|archivedate = 1 July 2015|df = dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Flamingo Land \u2013 Party In The Park June 2015|url = http://www.flamingoland.co.uk/party-in-the-park-june-2015.html|website = Flamingoland.co.uk|accessdate = 6 July 2015|first = Super|last = User}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.thanetgazette.co.uk/Calum-Scott-perform-Westwood-Cross-10th-birthday/story-26772200-detail/story.html|title = Calum Scott to perform at Westwood Cross' 10th birthday celebration weekend|date = 26 June 2015|accessdate = |website = Thanetgazette.co.uk|last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Visit Gibraltar \u2013 Events|url = http://www.visitgibraltar.gi/event/summer-nights-2015/230|website = Visitgibraltar.gi|accessdate = 9 July 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170814140909/http://www.visitgibraltar.gi/event/summer-nights-2015/230|archive-date = 14 August 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Britain's Got Talent star Calum Scott could be Star Search final judge|url = http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Britain-s-Got-Talent-star-Calum-Scott-Star-Search/story-26643657-detail/story.html|work = Hull Daily Mail|accessdate = 6 July 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150706084457/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Britain-s-Got-Talent-star-Calum-Scott-Star-Search/story-26643657-detail/story.html|archive-date = 6 July 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Dartford Festival 2015: Record numbers of visitors come to see Calum Scott from Britain's Got Talent and Andy Jordan from Made In Chelsea|url = http://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/thank-you-for-the-music-40397/|website=Kentonline.co.uk|accessdate = 20 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present: ''Only Human''===\n[[File:Calum Scott.png|thumb|upright|right|200px|Scott performing live at the Tabernacle, United Kingdom, in 2016.]]\nScott released his cover of \"Dancing On My Own\" independently on 15 April 2016. It became a sleeper hit, first hitting number 40 in the charts in May and climbing into the top 40 despite little radio airplay apart from on West Hull FM. It was then added to [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]]'s \"C List\" and reached number two on the [[UK Singles Chart]] on 5 August. In August 2016, it was certified platinum in the UK, having sold over 600,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/bpi_music/status/769187789543907329 |title=bpi music on Twitter: \"Huge congrats to @calumscott! His single 'Dancing On My Own' has shot from Gold to Platinum! #bpiAwards\" |publisher=[[Twitter]] |date=26 August 2016 |accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref> Scott announced on Twitter on 24 May that he had signed a record deal with [[Capitol Records]] for his debut album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/calumscottmusic/status/734885858684342272|title=Calum Scott |publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> Scott performed the song at television shows ''[[BBC Look North (East Yorkshire and Lincolnshire)|BBC Look North]]'', ''[[Lorraine (TV programme)|Lorraine]]'', ''[[Weekend (TV programme)|Weekend]]'', ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]'' and Brazilian show ''[[Encontro com F\u00e1tima Bernardes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title = BBC Look North (East Yorkshire & Lincolnshire) {{!}} Facebook|url = https://www.facebook.com/BBCLookNorth/videos/855688384518774/|website = Facebook.com|accessdate = 6 July 2015}}</ref> He also promoted the song on several radio stations, including [[BBC Radio Humberside]], [[Viking FM]], Radio Gibraltar, [[BFBS Radio]] and [[Gibraltar Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Calum Scott, 06/06/2015, James Hoggarth \u2013 BBC Radio Humberside|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02t69gw|website = BBC|accessdate = 6 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = #BGT finalist @calumscottmusic chats to @jameshoggarth about @BGT and the future|url = https://audioboom.com/boos/3256363-bgt-finalist-calumscottmusic-chats-to-jameshoggarth-about-bgt-and-the-future|website = AudioBoom.com|accessdate = 6 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Calum Scott in Gib|url = http://www.gbc.gi/radio/highlights/calum-scott-gib-44|website = Gbc.gi|accessdate = 20 July 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021101/http://www.gbc.gi/radio/highlights/calum-scott-gib-44|archive-date = 24 September 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> On 16 September, he released the promotional single \"[[:pt:Transformar (can\u00e7\u00e3o)|Transformar]]\" with Brazilian recording artist [[Ivete Sangalo]] as official theme of [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016 Summer Paralympics Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.purebreak.com.br/noticias/ivete-sangalo-lanca-transformar-musica-inedita-com-callum-scott-para-as-paralimpiadas-rio-2016/42216|title=Ivete Sangalo lan\u00e7a \"Transformar\", m\u00fasica in\u00e9dita com Calum Scott para as \"Paralimp\u00edadas Rio 2016\"|work=Pure Break|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> They performed the song at the closing ceremony of the Paralympics on 18 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opovo.com.br/app/divirta-se/2016/09/19/noticiasdivirtase,3659732/ivete-sangalo-brilha-na-cerimonia-de-encerramento-das-paralimpiadas-20.shtml|title=Ivete Sangalo brilha na cerim\u00f4nia de encerramento das Paralimp\u00edadas 2016|work=O Povo News|accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> It was revealed in September 2016 that \"Dancing On My Own\" was the most downloaded song of the summer in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|last=Copsey |first=Rob |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-official-top-40-biggest-songs-of-summer-2016-revealed__16181/ |title=The Official Top 40 Biggest Songs of Summer 2016 revealed |website=OfficialCharts.com |date=31 August 2016 |accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he toured the US and released the single \"[[You Are the Reason (Calum Scott song)|You Are the Reason]]\". Also in 2017, he began working on his debut album, ''[[Only Human (Calum Scott album)|Only Human]]'', which was released on 9 March 2018. A new version of \"You Are the Reason\" was released ahead of the album in early 2018 as a collaboration with [[Leona Lewis]], and was performed by the two on ''[[The One Show]]'' in February 2018. In May, Scott released \"[[What I Miss Most]]\" as the fourth single from ''Only Human''.\n\nIn October 2018, Scott released a new single titled \"[[No Matter What (Calum Scott song)|No Matter What]]\". Upon release, Scott said \"No Matter What\" is without question the most personal song I have ever written and the one I am most proud of. It's a song born from loneliness, acceptance and the heartbreaking but liberating tale of my coming out experience. What I love about this song is that it isn't just limited to a story of sexual identity, but about the relationship between parent and child and acceptance as a whole. This song didn't make my debut album because I simply wasn't ready at that time to give it to the world.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2018/10/the-purge-375/|title=The Purge 375|publisher=auspOp|date=20 October 2018|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Release details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"8\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Certification]]s\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br><ref name=uk>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/49237/calum-scott/|title=UK Charts|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref name=aus>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Calum+Scott|title=Discography Calum Scott|work=australian-charts.com|accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br>{{small|(FL)}}]]<br><ref name=bel>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Calum+Scott|title=Belgium Charts|language=Dutch|publisher=ultratop.be|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/calum-scott/chart-history/canadian-albums|title=Calum Scott Chart History: Canadian Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br><ref name=ire>{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Calum+Scott|title=Irish Charts|publisher=irish-charts.com Hung Medien|accessdate=4 October 2016}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Single Top 100|NLD]]<br><ref name=nld>{{cite web|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Calum+Scott|title=Dutch Charts|language=Dutch|publisher=dutchcharts.nl|accessdate=10 December 2016}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4464|title=NZ Top 40 Albums Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=19 March 2018|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/calum-scott/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Calum Scott Chart History: Billboard 200|work=Billboard|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Only Human (Calum Scott album)|Only Human]]''\n|\n* Released: 9 March 2018\n* Label: [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n* Formats: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[LP record|LP]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 4 || 5 || 35 || 27 || 19 || 75 || 26 || 66\n|\n* BPI: Silver<ref name=\"BPI\"/>\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of singles, with selected chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br><ref name=uk/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref name=aus/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br>{{small|(FL)}}]]<br><ref name=bel/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Tracklisten|DEN]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=44&y=2016&list=t40 |title=Track Top-40 Uge 43, 2016 |publisher=Hitlisten.NU |accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Irish Singles Chart|IRE]]<br><ref name=ire/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Single Top 100|NLD]]<br><ref name=nld/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=4286|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Scottish Singles and Albums Charts|SCO]]<br><ref>Peaks in Scotland:\n* \"Dancing on My Own\": {{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/22/2016-07-21/|title=15 July 2016 \u2013 21 July 2016 |publisher=Official Charts|accessdate=4 October 2016}}\n* \"Rhythm Inside\": {{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/22/2016-12-02/|title=2 December 2016 \u2013 8 December 2016 |publisher=Official Charts|accessdate=3 December 2016}}\n* \"You Are the Reason\": {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20180216/41/|title=16 February 2018 \u2013 22 February 2018 |publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=17 February 2018}}\n* \"What I Miss Most\": {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20180629/41/|title=29 June 2018 \u2013 5 July 2018 |publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=30 June 2018}}\n* \"No Matter What\": {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20190201/41/|title=1 February 2019 \u2013 7 February 2019 |publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Sverigetopplistan|SWE]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sverigetopplistan.se/ |title=Sverigetopplistan \u2013 Sveriges Officiella Topplista |publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]] |accessdate=22 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226145037/http://www.sverigetopplistan.se/ |archivedate=26 December 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|US<br>{{small|Adult}}]]<br /><ref name=\"adult\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/calum-scott/chart-history/adult-contemporary|title=Calum Scott Chart History: Adult Contemporary|work=Billboard|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Dancing On My Own#Calum Scott version|Dancing On My Own]]\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2016\n| 2 || 2 || 19 || 8 || 4 || 14 || 5 || 1 || 4 || 15\n|\n* [[British Phonographic Industry|BPI]]: 3\u00d7 Platinum<ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/brit-certified/| title=BRIT Certified - bpi|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=31 August 2018|format=enter \"Calum Scott\" into the \"Keywords\" box, then select \"Search\"}}</ref>\n* [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]]: 8\u00d7 Platinum<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesSinglesAccreds2019.htm|title=ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2019 Singles.|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=8 October 2019}}</ref>\n* [[IFPI Denmark|IFPI DEN]]: Gold<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=48&y=2016&list=t40|title=Track Top-40: Week 47 - 2016|publisher=Hitlisten|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Recorded Music NZ|RMNZ]]: Platinum<ref>{{cite certification|region=New Zealand|type=single|artist=Calum Scott|title=Dancing On My Own|recent=website|id=4304|accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]: 2\u00d7 Platinum<ref name=\"riaa.com\">https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Calum+scott#search_section</ref>\n| rowspan=\"4\"| ''Only Human''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Rhythm Inside (Calum Scott song)|Rhythm Inside]]\"\n| 90 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 23 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[You Are the Reason (Calum Scott song)|You Are the Reason]]\" \n<small>(''Solo and duet version with [[Leona Lewis]]'')</small>\n| 2017\n| 43 || 27 || \u2014{{efn|group=upper-alpha|\"You Are the Reason\" did not enter the Flemish Ultratop 50, peaked at number 24 on the [[Ultratop#Ultratip|Ultratip]] chart.<ref name=bel/>}} || \u2014 || 55 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 6 || \u2014{{efn|group=upper-alpha|\"You Are the Reason\" did not enter the [[Sverigetopplistan|Swedish Singellista Chart]], but peaked at number one on the Swedish Heatseeker Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/215?dspy=2019&dspp=39|title=Veckolista Heatseeker, vecka 39|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]]|accessdate=27 September 2019}}</ref>}} || 11\n|\n* BPI: Gold<ref name=\"BPI\"/>\n* [[IFPI Denmark|IFPI DEN]]: Gold\n* FIMI: Gold\n* Pro Musica Brasil: Gold\n* Music Canada: 2x Platinum\n* ARIA: 4\u00d7 Platinum<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/SinglesAccreds2018.htm|title=ARIA Charts - Accreditations - 2018 Singles|last=|first=|date=2018-12-31|publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association|accessdate=2019-01-28}}</ref>\n* RIAA: Platinum <ref name=\"riaa.com\"/>\n* \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[What I Miss Most]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/music/musicnews/calum-scott-new-single-what-miss-most-1142463.html|publisher=Female First|title=Calum Scott Drops New Single 'What I Miss Most'|date=6 May 2018|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/music-news/calum-scott-releases-new-single-what-i-miss-most/|title=Calum Scott releases new single What I Miss Most|publisher=Entertainment Focus|date=May 2018|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2018\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 83 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[No Matter What (Calum Scott song)|No Matter What]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/no-matter-what-single/1438691776|title=No Matter What|publisher=iTunes Australia|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>\n| \u2014 || 137 || \u2014{{efn|group=upper-alpha|\"No Matter What\" did not enter the Flemish Ultratop 50, peaked at number 46 on the Ultratip chart.<ref name=bel/>}} || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 53 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n| ''Only Human: Special Edition''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Undo\"<br><span style=\"font-size:85%;\"> (with [[Naughty Boy]] and [[Shenseea]])</span>\n| 2019\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n| ''Bungee Jumping''\n|-\n| colspan=\"15\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:8pt;\"| \"\u2014\" denotes releases that did not chart or were not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n====As featured artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Give Me Love\"<br><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">([[Don Diablo]] featuring Calum Scott)</span>\n| 2018\n| ''[[Future (Don Diablo album)|Future]]''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Love on Myself\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8520162/felix-jaehn-calum-scott-love-on-myself-video |title=Felix Jaehn & Calum Scott look inside themselves in 'Love On Myself' video: Watch |last=Bein |first=Kat |date=16 July 2019 |website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726041501/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8520162/felix-jaehn-calum-scott-love-on-myself-video |archive-date=26 July 2019 |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref> <br />{{small|([[Felix Jaehn]] featuring Calum Scott)}}\n| 2019\n| {{N/A|Non-album single}}\n|}\n\n===Promotional singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[:pt:Transformar (can\u00e7\u00e3o)|Transformar (Change)]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portalpopline.virgula.uol.com.br/ivete-sangalo-canta-tema-paralimpico-com-britanico-calum-scott-ouca-transformar/|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|title=Calum Scott and Ivete Sangalo sing \"Transformar\"|accessdate=19 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919125701/http://portalpopline.virgula.uol.com.br/ivete-sangalo-canta-tema-paralimpico-com-britanico-calum-scott-ouca-transformar/|archive-date=19 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><br><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(with [[Ivete Sangalo]])</span>\n| 2016\n| {{n/a|Non-album single}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Songwriting credits===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Artist(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:13em;\"| Album\n! scope=\"col\" | Credits\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Joke Is on Me\"\n| 2018\n| [[Boyzone]]\n| ''[[Thank You & Goodnight]]''\n| Co-writer\n|}\n\n'''Notes'''\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==Videography==\n===As lead artist===\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=text-align:center\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n