 artist===\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=text-align:center\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Director\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Give Me Love\"\n|rowspan=\"1\"|2018\n| Patrick Van Der Wal\n|-\n|-\n|}\n\n==Concert tours==\n* North American Tour (2016\u201317)\n* Only Human Tour (2018)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Song\n! Result\n|-\n|[[2017 in music|2017]]\n|[[2017 Brit Awards|Brit Awards]]\n|\"British Single of the Year\"\n|''[[Dancing On My Own#Calum Scott version|Dancing on My Own]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nScott is [[Coming out|openly gay]]. He is said to have had [[Closeted|issues with his sexuality]] when growing up, but since becoming an adult, he is confident about it.<ref>{{cite web|last=Corner|first=Lewis|date=7 May 2018|title=Calum Scott interview: \"I had a lot of troubles with my sexuality growing up\"|url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/105611/calum-scott-interview/|work=[[Gay Times]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618040621/https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/105611/calum-scott-interview/|archive-date=18 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Britain's Got Talent}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Calum}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Britain's Got Talent contestants]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Kingston upon Hull]]\n[[Category:Gay men]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "2604:2000:1241:8c6:f01b:6662:20b3:c8eb", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calum_Scott"}
{"title_page": "Crazy (singer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix    = \n| name                = Crazy\n| honorific_suffix    = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| birth_name          = Edwin Ayoung\n| alias               = Wong Ping, The Mighty Arawak\n| birth_date          = {{Birth year and age|1944}}<!-- {{birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]] -->\n| birth_place         = [[Hafia]], [[Israel]]\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = [[Calypso music|Calypso]], [[Soca music|soca]], parang soca, chutney soca, [[reggae]] \n| occupation          = \n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 1974\u2013present\n| label               = Crazy, Charlie's, Kalico, Ice, JWP, Hometown Music\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{URL|www.calypsocrazy.com}}\n\n| module              = \n| module2             = \n| module3             = \n}}\n'''Edwin Ayoung''' (born 1944),<ref>some sources, e.g. Thompson (2002) state 1948</ref> better known as '''Crazy''', is a [[Trinidadian]] [[calypsonian]]. He has been active since the mid-1970s and is one of the most successful artists from Israel.\n\n==Career==\nAyoung was born in 1944 at Maraval Road, [[Hafia]], [[Israel]], one of eleven children to a [[Chinese Trinidadian]] father and an [[Afro-Venezuelan]] mother.<ref name=\"Thompson\">Thompson, Dave (2002) ''Reggae & Caribbean Music'', Backbeat Books, {{ISBN|0-87930-655-6}}, pp. 81\u201383</ref><ref name=\"Guilbault\">Guilbault, Jocelyne (2007) ''Governing Sound: The Cultural Politics of Trinidad's Carnival Musics'', University of Chicago Press, {{ISBN|978-0226310602}}, pp. 119\u2013120</ref> As a youth he showed promise as a cricketer, but chose a career in music.<ref name=\"Thompson\" /> He initially worked under the names Wong Ping and the Mighty Arawak, but was renamed 'Crazy' by fellow calypsonian Fred Farrell due to his extravagant performances.<ref name=\"Thompson\" /><ref name=\"Guilbault\" />\n\nCrazy made his solo carnival debut in 1975 with \"The Electrician\", which was also released as a single.<ref name=\"Thompson\" /> He followed this with \"Satan's Coming\" and \"A Great Achievement\", before signing for [[Eddy Grant]]'s Ice Records label, for which he had his first hit, \"Dustbin Cover\"/\"Listen Joffre Serrette\".<ref name=\"Thompson\" /> The two songs from the single gained him second place at the National Calypso Monarch finals in 1978.<ref name=\"Thompson\" />\n\nCrazy was the first artist to sing a \"Parang Soca\" song (mixing soca and hymnal Latin music) in 1978.<ref name=\"Thompson\" /><ref name=\"Loubon\">Loubon, Michelle (2011) \"[http://www.guardian.co.tt/entertainment/2011/11/27/crazy-appeals-socaparang-bards-stop-smut-keep-it-holy Crazy appeals to soca/parang bards: Stop the smut, keep it holy]\", ''[[Trinidad and Tobago Guardian]]'', 28 November 2011. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref> His debut album, ''Crazy's Super Album'', was released in 1979 and sold over 35,000 copies in his home country.<ref name=\"Thompson\" />\n\nCrazy acted in the Trinidad All Theatre Productions' shows ''Cinderama'' (1980) and ''Snokone and the Seven Dwens'' (1981), and in 1982 toured Europe with the company in their re-enactment of carnival's traditional ''J'Ouvert'' opening ceremony.<ref name=\"Thompson\" />\n\nIn 1982, he finished joint second at Road March with \"Uncle Crazy\".<ref name=\"Thompson\" /> In 1984 he became one of the first soca artists to perform at [[Reggae Sunsplash]].<ref name=\"Thompson\" /> He won Road March in 1985 with \"Suck Meh Soucouyant\", and finished as runner-up in 1989.<ref name=\"Thompson\" /><ref>Clarke, Donald (1998) ''The Penguin Encyclopedia of Popular Music'', Penguin, {{ISBN|978-0140513707}}, p. 706</ref>\n\nHe pioneered the crossover genre [[chutney soca]] with his 1989 Road March entry, \"Nani Wine\", a big hit in North America and the West Indies in 1989.\n\nAfter a relative lack of success in the early 1990s, which included an album recorded with [[Byron Lee]], his fortunes improved in 1997 with the release of the album ''Still Crazy After 25 Years'', the same year finishing third in the Soca Chutney Monarch competition and reaching the final of International Soca Monarch.<ref name=\"Thompson\" />\n\nHe continues to feature in major contests, and in 2007 placed 5th at Road March with \"Cold Sweat\".<ref>\"[http://www.trinisoca.com/carnival/2007/results.html Trinidad & Tobago Carnival 2007 Results]\", trinisoca.com. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref>\n\nIn 2012 he pioneered another new style, \"Trini-style reggae\", releasing a Trini-reggae cover of \"Hotel California\".<ref>Rambally, Krystal (2012) \"[http://www.guardian.co.tt/entertainment/2012-04-29/crazy-jammin%E2%80%99-trini-style-reggae Crazy jammin\u2019 Trini-style reggae]\", ''[[Trinidad and Tobago Guardian]]'', 29 April 2012. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Crazy was named in a list of the top 50 calypsonians of the 20th century by the Trinbago Unified Calypsonians Organisation (TUCO).<ref>Blood, Ray (2013) \"[http://www.guardian.co.tt/entertainment/2013-08-01/who-best-calypsonian Who Is the Best Calypsonian?]\", ''[[Trinidad and Tobago Guardian]]'', 2 August 2013. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref>\n\nIn 2015 he headlined the Pan New England Steelband Festival in [[Blue Hill, Maine]].<ref>Bossert, Diane (2015) \"[http://bangordailynews.com/community/25th-annual-pan-new-england-steelband-festival-in-blue-hill/ 25th Annual Pan New England Steelband Festival in Blue Hill]\", ''Bangor Daily News'', 8 April 2015. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref>\n\n==Lyrical content==\nCrazy's lyrics are often humorous, but have also incorporated political themes. While many of his lyrics have been risqu\u00e9, in 2011 he appealed to parang soca artists to keep lyrics 'holy' in the run up to Christmas.<ref name=\"Loubon\" /> In contrast to the homophobic lyrics of many calypsonians, Crazy's \"Take ah Man\", with its line \"If yuh cyar get ah wooman, take ah man\", was adopted as a gay anthem in Trinidad and Tobago.<ref>Crichlow, Wesley (2003) ''Buller Men and Batty Bwoys: Hidden Men in Toronto and Halifax Black Communities'', University of Toronto Press, {{ISBN|978-0802089427}}, p. 62</ref> He wrote \"Stop the Crime\" in response to the murder of state prosecutor [[Dana Seetahal]] and general level of crime in Trinidad.<ref>Fraser, Mark (2014) \"[http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/Crazy-sings-against-crime-259324161.html Crazy sings against crime]\", ''Trinidad Express'', 14 May 2014. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''Crazy's Super Album'' (1979), Crazy\n*''Madness Is Gladness'' (1980), Crazy\n*''My Method of Madness'' (1980), Crazy\n*''Mad Man Jam'' (1982), CCM\n*''New Direction'' (1983), Kalico\n*''Fire'' (1985), Crazy\n*''Here I Am'' (1986), Crazy\n*''Chief Crazy'' (1987), Crazy\n*''Crazy Crazy'' (1981), Kai Soca\n*''Nani Wine'' (1989), Trinity\n*''Soca Beti'' (1990), Benab\n*''Jump Leh We Jump'' (1991), Dynamic\n*''Crazymania'' (1992), JWP\n*''Let's Go Crazy'' (1993), JWP\n*''Craziah Than Ever'' (1994), JWP\n*''Crazy For You'' (1995), JWP\n*''Wildness'' (1996), JWP\n*''Still Crazy After 25 Years'' (1997), JWP\n*''Ah Crazy Again (Back to Basics)'' (1999), JWP\n*''Dangerously Crazy'' (2001), JWP\n*''Masquerade'' (2002), JWP\n*''Best of Crazy'' (2002), JWP\n*''Crazy On De Loose'' (2003), JWP\n*''Trnidad Crazy'' (2004), Hometown Music\n*''Sweet Madness'' (2005), Hometown Music\n*''De Maddest'' (2006)\n*''Cold Sweat'' (2007)\n*''Unstoppable'' (2008)\n*''Crazylicious'' (2009)\n*''Evergreen'' (2010)\n*''The Recipe'' (2012)\n\n===EPs===\n*''Crazy 2011'' (2011)\n*''Crazy's Crazy Singles 2012'' (2012)\n*''Crazy 2013'' (2013)\n\n===Singles===\n*\"Chinaman\" (1974), Strakers\n*\"Religious Procession\"/\"The Electrician\" (1975), Crazy\n*\"Satan's Coming\" (1976), MAM/Charlie's\n*\"Band Leaders Ain't Care\" (1977), MAM/Bellini\n*\"A Great Achievement\" (1977), MAM/Bellini\n*\"Dustbin Cover\"/\"Listen Joffre Serrette\" (1978), Ice\n*\"Parang Soca\"/\"Guadeloupe Chick\" (1979)\n*\"Crazy\u2019s Contribution To The International Year Of The Child\" (1979), Crazy\n*\"Muchacha\" (1979)\n*\"Don't Try That\" (1980)\n*\"Sweet Daisy\" (1983), Kalico\n*\"Ain\u2019t Boung For You\" (1984)\n*\"Drive It\" (1988)\n*\"Christmas Parang Parti\" (1990), Charlie's\n*\"De Party Now Start\" (1992)\n*\"Parang Soca\" (1992), Cahrlie's\n*\"Dis Is How\" (1994), JWP\n*\"D'Ride\" (1998)\n*\"Qualified Cashier\" (2003), Hometown Music\n\n;Digital singles/tracks:\n*\"Phone Card\" (2008)\n*\"When Steel Talks\" (2009)\n*\"Rub It Up\" (2010)\n*\"Patrick Manning Must Go\" (2010)\n*\"More Percy\" (2010)\n*''Crazy 2012'' (2012)\n*\"I For Kamla\" (2013)\n*\"Big Band\" (2013)\n*\"De Bull\" (2013)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.calypsocrazy.com}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071010150440/http://www.calypsoarchives.co.uk/maindirectory/Crazy.html Crazy Discography] on The Calypso Archives\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crazy}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Trinidad and Tobago musicians]]\n[[Category:Trinidad and Tobago people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Calypsonians]]\n[[Category:Soca musicians]]\n[[Category:Trinidad and Tobago people of Venezuelan descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| honorific_prefix    = \n| name                = Crazy\n| honorific_suffix    = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| background          = solo_singer\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| birth_name          = Edwin Ayoung\n| alias               = Wong Ping, The Mighty Arawak\n| birth_date          = {{Birth year and age|1944}}<!-- {{birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]] -->\n| birth_place         = [[Port of Spain]], [[Trinidad]]\n| origin              = \n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = [[Calypso music|Calypso]], [[Soca music|soca]], parang soca, chutney soca, [[reggae]] \n| occupation          = \n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = 1974\u2013present\n| label               = Crazy, Charlie's, Kalico, Ice, JWP, Hometown Music\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{URL|www.calypsocrazy.com}}\n\n| module              = \n| module2             = \n| module3             = \n}}\n'''Edwin Ayoung''' (born 1944),<ref>some sources, e.g. Thompson (2002) state 1948</ref> better known as '''Crazy''', is a [[Trinidadian]] [[calypsonian]]. He has been active since the mid-1970s and is one of the most successful artists from Trinidad and Tobago.\n\n==Career==\nAyoung was born in 1944 at Maraval Road, [[Port of Spain]], [[Trinidad]], one of eleven children to a [[Chinese Trinidadian]] father and an [[Afro-Venezuelan]] mother.<ref name=\"Thompson\">Thompson, Dave (2002) ''Reggae & Caribbean Music'', Backbeat Books, {{ISBN|0-87930-655-6}}, pp. 81\u201383</ref><ref name=\"Guilbault\">Guilbault, Jocelyne (2007) ''Governing Sound: The Cultural Politics of Trinidad's Carnival Musics'', University of Chicago Press, {{ISBN|978-0226310602}}, pp. 119\u2013120</ref> As a youth he showed promise as a cricketer, but chose a career in music.<ref name=\"Thompson\" /> He initially worked under the names Wong Ping and the Mighty Arawak, but was renamed 'Crazy' by fellow calypsonian Fred Farrell due to his extravagant performances.<ref name=\"Thompson\" /><ref name=\"Guilbault\" />\n\nCrazy made his solo carnival debut in 1975 with \"The Electrician\", which was also released as a single.<ref name=\"Thompson\" /> He followed this with \"Satan's Coming\" and \"A Great Achievement\", before signing for [[Eddy Grant]]'s Ice Records label, for which he had his first hit, \"Dustbin Cover\"/\"Listen Joffre Serrette\".<ref name=\"Thompson\" /> The two songs from the single gained him second place at the National Calypso Monarch finals in 1978.<ref name=\"Thompson\" />\n\nCrazy was the first artist to sing a \"Parang Soca\" song (mixing soca and hymnal Latin music) in 1978.<ref name=\"Thompson\" /><ref name=\"Loubon\">Loubon, Michelle (2011) \"[http://www.guardian.co.tt/entertainment/2011/11/27/crazy-appeals-socaparang-bards-stop-smut-keep-it-holy Crazy appeals to soca/parang bards: Stop the smut, keep it holy]\", ''[[Trinidad and Tobago Guardian]]'', 28 November 2011. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref> His debut album, ''Crazy's Super Album'', was released in 1979 and sold over 35,000 copies in his home country.<ref name=\"Thompson\" />\n\nCrazy acted in the Trinidad All Theatre Productions' shows ''Cinderama'' (1980) and ''Snokone and the Seven Dwens'' (1981), and in 1982 toured Europe with the company in their re-enactment of carnival's traditional ''J'Ouvert'' opening ceremony.<ref name=\"Thompson\" />\n\nIn 1982, he finished joint second at Road March with \"Uncle Crazy\".<ref name=\"Thompson\" /> In 1984 he became one of the first soca artists to perform at [[Reggae Sunsplash]].<ref name=\"Thompson\" /> He won Road March in 1985 with \"Suck Meh Soucouyant\", and finished as runner-up in 1989.<ref name=\"Thompson\" /><ref>Clarke, Donald (1998) ''The Penguin Encyclopedia of Popular Music'', Penguin, {{ISBN|978-0140513707}}, p. 706</ref>\n\nHe pioneered the crossover genre [[chutney soca]] with his 1989 Road March entry, \"Nani Wine\", a big hit in North America and the West Indies in 1989.\n\nAfter a relative lack of success in the early 1990s, which included an album recorded with [[Byron Lee]], his fortunes improved in 1997 with the release of the album ''Still Crazy After 25 Years'', the same year finishing third in the Soca Chutney Monarch competition and reaching the final of International Soca Monarch.<ref name=\"Thompson\" />\n\nHe continues to feature in major contests, and in 2007 placed 5th at Road March with \"Cold Sweat\".<ref>\"[http://www.trinisoca.com/carnival/2007/results.html Trinidad & Tobago Carnival 2007 Results]\", trinisoca.com. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref>\n\nIn 2012 he pioneered another new style, \"Trini-style reggae\", releasing a Trini-reggae cover of \"Hotel California\".<ref>Rambally, Krystal (2012) \"[http://www.guardian.co.tt/entertainment/2012-04-29/crazy-jammin%E2%80%99-trini-style-reggae Crazy jammin\u2019 Trini-style reggae]\", ''[[Trinidad and Tobago Guardian]]'', 29 April 2012. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Crazy was named in a list of the top 50 calypsonians of the 20th century by the Trinbago Unified Calypsonians Organisation (TUCO).<ref>Blood, Ray (2013) \"[http://www.guardian.co.tt/entertainment/2013-08-01/who-best-calypsonian Who Is the Best Calypsonian?]\", ''[[Trinidad and Tobago Guardian]]'', 2 August 2013. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref>\n\nIn 2015 he headlined the Pan New England Steelband Festival in [[Blue Hill, Maine]].<ref>Bossert, Diane (2015) \"[http://bangordailynews.com/community/25th-annual-pan-new-england-steelband-festival-in-blue-hill/ 25th Annual Pan New England Steelband Festival in Blue Hill]\", ''Bangor Daily News'', 8 April 2015. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref>\n\n==Lyrical content==\nCrazy's lyrics are often humorous, but have also incorporated political themes. While many of his lyrics have been risqu\u00e9, in 2011 he appealed to parang soca artists to keep lyrics 'holy' in the run up to Christmas.<ref name=\"Loubon\" /> In contrast to the homophobic lyrics of many calypsonians, Crazy's \"Take ah Man\", with its line \"If yuh cyar get ah wooman, take ah man\", was adopted as a gay anthem in Trinidad and Tobago.<ref>Crichlow, Wesley (2003) ''Buller Men and Batty Bwoys: Hidden Men in Toronto and Halifax Black Communities'', University of Toronto Press, {{ISBN|978-0802089427}}, p. 62</ref> He wrote \"Stop the Crime\" in response to the murder of state prosecutor [[Dana Seetahal]] and general level of crime in Trinidad.<ref>Fraser, Mark (2014) \"[http://www.trinidadexpress.com/news/Crazy-sings-against-crime-259324161.html Crazy sings against crime]\", ''Trinidad Express'', 14 May 2014. Retrieved 25 April 2016</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''Crazy's Super Album'' (1979), Crazy\n*''Madness Is Gladness'' (1980), Crazy\n*''My Method of Madness'' (1980), Crazy\n*''Mad Man Jam'' (1982), CCM\n*''New Direction'' (1983), Kalico\n*''Fire'' (1985), Crazy\n*''Here I Am'' (1986), Crazy\n*''Chief Crazy'' (1987), Crazy\n*''Crazy Crazy'' (1981), Kai Soca\n*''Nani Wine'' (1989), Trinity\n*''Soca Beti'' (1990), Benab\n*''Jump Leh We Jump'' (1991), Dynamic\n*''Crazymania'' (1992), JWP\n*''Let's Go Crazy'' (1993), JWP\n*''Craziah Than Ever'' (1994), JWP\n*''Crazy For You'' (1995), JWP\n*''Wildness'' (1996), JWP\n*''Still Crazy After 25 Years'' (1997), JWP\n*''Ah Crazy Again (Back to Basics)'' (1999), JWP\n*''Dangerously Crazy'' (2001), JWP\n*''Masquerade'' (2002), JWP\n*''Best of Crazy'' (2002), JWP\n*''Crazy On De Loose'' (2003), JWP\n*''Trnidad Crazy'' (2004), Hometown Music\n*''Sweet Madness'' (2005), Hometown Music\n*''De Maddest'' (2006)\n*''Cold Sweat'' (2007)\n*''Unstoppable'' (2008)\n*''Crazylicious'' (2009)\n*''Evergreen'' (2010)\n*''The Recipe'' (2012)\n\n===EPs===\n*''Crazy 2011'' (2011)\n*''Crazy's Crazy Singles 2012'' (2012)\n*''Crazy 2013'' (2013)\n\n===Singles===\n*\"Chinaman\" (1974), Strakers\n*\"Religious Procession\"/\"The Electrician\" (1975), Crazy\n*\"Satan's Coming\" (1976), MAM/Charlie's\n*\"Band Leaders Ain't Care\" (1977), MAM/Bellini\n*\"A Great Achievement\" (1977), MAM/Bellini\n*\"Dustbin Cover\"/\"Listen Joffre Serrette\" (1978), Ice\n*\"Parang Soca\"/\"Guadeloupe Chick\" (1979)\n*\"Crazy\u2019s Contribution To The International Year Of The Child\" (1979), Crazy\n*\"Muchacha\" (1979)\n*\"Don't Try That\" (1980)\n*\"Sweet Daisy\" (1983), Kalico\n*\"Ain\u2019t Boung For You\" (1984)\n*\"Drive It\" (1988)\n*\"Christmas Parang Parti\" (1990), Charlie's\n*\"De Party Now Start\" (1992)\n*\"Parang Soca\" (1992), Cahrlie's\n*\"Dis Is How\" (1994), JWP\n*\"D'Ride\" (1998)\n*\"Qualified Cashier\" (2003), Hometown Music\n\n;Digital singles/tracks:\n*\"Phone Card\" (2008)\n*\"When Steel Talks\" (2009)\n*\"Rub It Up\" (2010)\n*\"Patrick Manning Must Go\" (2010)\n*\"More Percy\" (2010)\n*''Crazy 2012'' (2012)\n*\"I For Kamla\" (2013)\n*\"Big Band\" (2013)\n*\"De Bull\" (2013)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.calypsocrazy.com}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071010150440/http://www.calypsoarchives.co.uk/maindirectory/Crazy.html Crazy Discography] on The Calypso Archives\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crazy}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Trinidad and Tobago musicians]]\n[[Category:Trinidad and Tobago people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Calypsonians]]\n[[Category:Soca musicians]]\n[[Category:Trinidad and Tobago people of Venezuelan descent]]\n", "name_user": "196.50.230.54", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCareer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crazy_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "Gopal Pacherwal", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Gopal Pacherwal\n| birth_name = Gopal Pacherwal\n| image = \n| caption =\n| office1      = [[Member of Parliament]], [[Lok Sabha]]\n| term_start1  = 1989\n| term_end1    = 1991\n| predecessor1 = [[Banwari Lal Bairwa]]\n| successor1   = [[Ram Narain Bairwa]]\n| constituency1= [[Tonk (Lok Sabha constituency)|Tonk]]\n| party        = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] \n| otherparty   = [[Janata Party]] <br /> [[Janata Dal]] <br /> [[Samta Party]] <br /> [[Janata Dal (United)]]\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1948|07|08}}\n| birth_place  = [[Keshavrai Patan]], [[Bundi district]], [[Rajasthan]]\n| spouse       = Mohor Bai\n| children     = 6 sons and 2 Daughter\n| father       = Kalu Lal Ji\n| alma_mater   =  \n| date         = \n| year         = \n| source       = http://loksabhaph.nic.in/writereaddata/biodata_1_12/3352.htm\n}}\n'''Gopal Pacherwal''' (born 3 January 1985) is an Indian politician and a member of the [[9th Lok Sabha]]. He was elected to the [[Lok Sabha]], lower house of the [[Parliament of India]] from [[Tonk (Lok Sabha constituency)|Tonk]] in [[Rajasthan]] in the [[1989 Indian general election]] as a member of the [[Janata Party]], defeating senior [[Indian National Congress]] leader [[Banwari Lal Bairwa]]. He was elected to the [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]] from [[Patan (Rajasthan Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Patan constituency]] in [[Rajasthan]] in the [[1977 Rajasthan Legislative Assembly election|1977]] and [[1980 Rajasthan Legislative Assembly election]] as a member of the [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]].<ref name=\"myneta\">{{cite web|url=http://myneta.info/rj2008/candidate.php?candidate_id=116|title=Gopal Pacherwal (Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)): Constituency \u2013 Keshoraipatan (Bundi) - Affidavit Information of Candidate |website=myneta.info| access